{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> χαίρω</b>, <br /> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.191, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> <i>imperative</i> χαιρόντων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hercules Furens” 575 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>imperfect</i>, <i>Epic dialect</i> χαῖρον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.156 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], <i>Ionic dialect</i> χαίρεσκον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 18.259 \">Refs</a>]: <i>future</i> χαιρήσω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 20.363, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.128, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 64, 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.101, 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Anabasis” 5.20.6 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>reduplicate</i> <i>infinitive</i> κεχᾰρησέμεν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.98 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; later χᾰρῶ variant in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Rev.11.10 \">NT</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ἐχαίρησα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Lucullus” 25 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> κεχάρηκα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 764 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], <i>participle</i> <b>-ηκώς</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.42, etc., _Epic dialect_ _accusative_ κεχᾰρηότα, _plural_ -ότας, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.312, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Fragmenta” 77:\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] —<i>middle</i> (in same sense), χαίρομαι, noted as a barbarism in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Pax” 291 (see. Scholia), but found in “BCH” 36.622 (Perinthus, written χέρ-), 3rd c.AD: Alexander Aphrodisiensis Philosophus “Problemata - Physici et Medici Graeci Minores” 1.20, +others: \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>future</i> χᾰρήσομαι Ps.-[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Philopatr.” 24, (συγ-) 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 30.18.1, 1st c.BC: Diodorus Siculus Historicus 31.15 \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]; <i>Doric dialect</i> χαρησοῦμαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Pythagoras Philosophus “Ep.” 3.7; χᾰροῦμαι LXX Zech.4.10, (κατα-)LXX.Pro.1.26\">LXX+4th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> κεχᾰρήσομαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 23.266 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist 1</i> <i>participle</i> χαιρησάμενος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “BGU” 742 ii 3 (2nd c.AD)\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]: <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>aorist 1</i> χήρατο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.270; ἐχ- 3rd c.AD: Oppianus Apamensis Epicus “Cynegetica” 1.509, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>participle</i> χηράμενος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Anthologia Graeca” 7.198 (1st c.AD: Leonidas Alexandrinus Epigrammaticus)\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]: <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>reduplicate</i> <i>aorist</i> 2, <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> κεχάροντο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 16.600 (χάροντο 4th c.AD(?): Quintus Smyrnaeus Epicus 6.315)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>optative</i> <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>singular</i> and <i>plural</i> κεχάροιτο, -οίατο, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.249, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.256:\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] —<i>passive</i> (in same sense), <i>aorist 2</i> ἐχάρην [ᾰ] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7.54 \">Refs</a>], etc., <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>singular</i> χάρη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5.682, 13.609 \">Refs</a>]; <i>subjunctive</i> χᾰρῇς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 606c; _optative_ χᾰρείη 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 6.481 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>infinitive</i> χᾰρῆναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Simonides Lyricus 164 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; <i>participle</i> χᾰρείς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 10.541, 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica 118, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “I.” 6(5).10, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Thesmophoriazusae” 981 (Lyric poetry), etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>perfect</i> κεχάρημαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “hymnus ad Bacchum” 7.10, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Aulidensis” 200 (Lyric poetry), 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 389 (_anapaest meter_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>participle</i> κεχαρμένος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 1122, “Tr.” 529 (Lyric poetry), “Cyc.” 367 (Lyric poetry): \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>pluperfect</i> <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>singular</i> and <i>plural</i> κεχάρητο, -ηντο, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 65, “hymnus ad Cererem” 458 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>rejoice, be glad,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.111, 21.347, etc.; γραῦς ἥδε οἰνοφόρος κεχαρημένη ὧδε κάθηται “IG” 12(8).679 (Scyros, 2nd c.BC): χ. θυμῷ 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.191, +others; ἐν θυμῷ 24.491, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 22.411; φρεσὶν ᾗσι 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 13.609; φρένα 6.481 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; χ. νόῳ <b>to rejoice</b> in wardly, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.78; χαίρει δέ μοι ἦτορ 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.647; αὐτὰρ ἐμὸν κῆρ χ. 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.260; χ. καὶ γελᾶν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 1300; ἥδομαι καὶ χαίρομαι κεὐφραίνομαι 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Pax” 291 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to λυπεῖσθαι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 266.3, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 555, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to ἀλγεῖν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Tr.” 1119. \">Refs</a>] —Constr., <br /><Level3><b>__1</b></Level3> with <i>dative</i> <i>of things</i>, <b>rejoice at, take pleasure in</b> a thing, νίκῃ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.312; φήμῃ 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.35; δώρῳ 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 358; μόλπᾳ 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica “Papyrus fragments” in E. Diehl, 25.5, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1070, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Menexenus” 238d, etc.: with _dative_ _person_, χαῖρε.. ἀνδρὶ δικαίῳ 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.52 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; with a <i>participle</i> added, χάρη δ᾽ ἄρα οἱ προσιόντι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.682, compare 24.706, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.463: with Preps., χαίρειν ἐπί τινι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 926, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.6.35, “Cyr.” 8.4.12, 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 2.30, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 739d, etc.; πρὸς τοῖς παιδικοῖς 5th c.BC: Eupolis Comicus 327 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; with a <i>participle</i> added, ἐπ᾽ ἐξεργασμένοις κακοῖσι χ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 1040, compare 1033: rarely ἔν τινι 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 996 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 1119: also with _dative_ modi, χ. γέλωτι\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <b>express one's joy</b> by laughter, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 8.1.33. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__1.b</b></Level4> of a plant, χαίρει ὑφάμμοις χωρίοις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 6.5.2; also ἡ κύστις χ. τῇ χολῇ 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 19.646. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> rarely with <i>accusative</i>, with a <i>participle</i> added, χαίρω δέ σ᾽ εὐτυχοῦντα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Rhesus” 390; τοὺς γὰρ εὐσεβεῖς θεοὶ θνῄσκοντας οὐ χ. [prev. author] “Hipp.” 1340 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χαίρω σ᾽ [ἐλθόντα] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “fragment” 673 \">Refs</a>] (this usage is said to be Oropian, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Etymologicum Magnum” 808.4). \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__2.b</b></Level4> with a <i>neuter</i> <i>adjective</i>, ταὐτὰ λυπεῖσθαι καὶ ταὐτὰ χαίρειν τοῖς πολλοῖς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.292: with _accusative_ _cognate_, ἁπλῆν χαίρειν ἡδονήν 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1154b26; χ. ἀνδραπόδων τινὰ χαράν 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.1091e. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> with <i>participle</i>, χαίρω.. τὸν μῦθον ἀκούσας <b>I rejoice at</b> having heard, <b>am glad to</b> hear, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.185, compare 7.54, 11.73; χαίρουσιν βίοτον νήποινον ἔδοντες 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.377, compare 12.380, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 55; χαίρω.. κόμπον ἱείς 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 8.49; χαίρεις ὁρῶν φῶς, πατέρα δ᾽ οὐ χαίρειν δοκεῖ; 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Alcestis” 691; χαίρω φειδόμενος 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 247; θωπευόμενος χαίρεις [prev. author] “Eq.” 1116 (Lyric poetry), compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 191e, etc. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__3.b</b></Level4> with <i>participle</i> <i>present</i>, <b>delight in</b> doing, <b>to be wont</b> to do, χρεώμενοι χαίρουσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.236, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 449, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 764, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 318d, 346c, 358a. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> χαίρειν ὅττι or ὅτι.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.51, 526, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 5.46 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἐχάρην καὶ ἐθρασυνάμην ὅτι ἔμαθον.. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Metrodorus Epigrammaticus “fragment” 42\">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]; χ. οὕνεκα.. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.200. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> with <i>negative</i>, especially with <i>future</i>, οὐ χαιρήσεις <b>thou wilt</b> or <b>shalt</b> not <b>rejoice,</b> i.e. <b>thou shalt</b> not <b>go unpunished, shalt repent</b> it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 64; οὐ χαιρήσετον [prev. author] “Eq.” 235; so οὐδέ τιν᾽ οἴω Τρώων χαιρήσειν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 20.363, compare 15.98, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.249, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 186 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἀλλ᾽ οὐδ᾽ ὣς Κῦρός γε χαιρήσει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.128 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; with an <i>interrogative</i>, σὺ.. χαιρήσειν νομίζει; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Alexander” 51 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]: rarely with other tenses, ὅπως ἂν μὴ χαίρωσιν. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 19.299; οὐκ ἐχαίρησεν 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Lucullus” 25: for a similar use of the \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<i>participle</i>, see below [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"IV.  2. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> frequently in <i>imperative</i> χαῖρε, dual χαίρετον, <i>plural</i> χαίρετε, as a form of greeting, <br /><Level3><b>__III.1</b></Level3> at meeting, <b>hail, welcome</b> (especially in the morning, <i>accusative</i> to [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Dio Cassius Historicus 69.18, compare 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Laps.”), 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.197, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 13.229, etc.; χαῖρε, ξεῖνε, παρ᾽ ἄμμι φιλήσεαι 1.123; strengthened, οὖλέ τε, καὶ μάλα χαῖρε, θεοὶ δέ τοι ὄλβια δοῖεν 24.402; χαῖρέ μοι 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.19, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1137; repeated, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 996, 1014 (both Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 91, etc.; χαῖρ᾽ ὡς μέγιστα, χαῖρε [prev. author] “Ph.” 462 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; in greeting one's native land, the sun, etc., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 508, 22, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1453 (_anapaest meter_). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__III.1.b</b></Level4> sometimes implied in the use of χαίρω, κῆρυξ Ἀχαιῶν, χαῖρε.. Answ. χαίρω I <b>accept the greeting,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 538 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; νῦν πᾶσι χαίρω, νῦν με πᾶς ἀσπάζεται I <b>hear the word</b> χαῖρε from all, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 596: so in \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i>, τὸ χαίρειν uncertain reading in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Charmides” 164e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χαίρειν δὲ τὸν κήρυκα προὐννέπω I bid him <b>welcome,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 227; προσειπών τινα χ. οὐκ ἀντιπροσερρήθη 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 3.13.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but χαίρειν τἄλλ᾽ ἐγώ σ᾽ ἐφίεμαι I bid thee <b>have thy pleasure,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 112. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__III.1.c</b></Level4> <i>infinitive</i> alone at the beginning of letters, Κῦρος Κυαζάρῃ χαίρειν (i.e. λέγει) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 4.5.27, compare 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 14.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; used by Alexander the Great to Phocion as a mark of respect, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Duris Epigrammaticus 51J. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> at leavetaking, <b>fare-thee-well,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.205, 13.59, 15.151; χαῖρε πόλλ᾽ ὦδελφέ 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 164; _plural_, χαίρετε πολλάκι 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 1.144 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; frequently put into the mouth of the dying, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 863, “Tr.” 921, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 116d, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: hence in sepulchral inscriptions, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 7.203, etc. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__III.2.b</b></Level4> hence, <i>imperative</i> χαιρέτω, χαιρόντων, <b>have done with.., away with</b>.., εἴτ᾽ ἐγένετο ἄνθρωπος εἴτ᾽ ἐστὶ δαίμων, χαιρέτω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.96; χαιρέτω βουλεύματα τὰ πρόσθεν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 1044, χαιρόντων πόνοι [prev. author] “HF” 575; compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 199a, “Lg.” 636d, 886d. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__III.2.c</b></Level4> ἐᾶν χαίρειν τινά or τι <b>dismiss from one's mind, put away, renounce,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.23, 9.41, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 1187, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 63e, “Prt.” 348a, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 7.3.23, etc.; συχνὰ χ. ἐᾶν τινα 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Philebus” 59b; ἐλευθερίαν μακρὰ χ. ἐᾶν 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Apol.” 3; μακρὰ χ. εἰποῦσα 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “Varia Historia” 12.1; πόλλα μοι τὰν Πωλυανάκτιδα παῖδα χαίρην 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica 86; τὴν Κύπριν πόλλ᾽ ἐγὼ χαίρειν λέγω 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 113, compare 1059, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 188a; χ. κελεύων πολλὰ τοὺς Ἀχαρνέας 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 200; εἰπεῖν χαίρειν τινά “Ath.Mitt.” 56.131 (Milet., Hellenistic), compare 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Dem.Enc.” 50; χαίρειν προσαγορεύειν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 322 (_metaphorically_ in 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 771a); χαίρειν προσειπεῖν 5th c.BC: Eupolis Comicus 308: less frequently with _dative_ _person_ (never with ἐᾶν χ.), πολλὰ χαίρειν ξυμφοραῖς καταξιῶ 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 572 (nisi to be read ξυμφοράς); φράσαι.. χαίρειν Ἀθηναίοισι 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 609 (troch.); πολλὰ εἰπόντα χ. τῷ ἀληθεῖ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 272e, compare “Phd.” 64c, “R.” 406d, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 4.1.31 (codices, perhaps ἀλλήλους), 4th c.AD: Julianus Imperator \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]<b>ad Them.</b>255a. <br /><Level3><b>__III.3</b></Level3> on other occasions, as in comforting, <b>be of good cheer,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.408; at meals, 4.60, 18.122 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; χαῖρε, γύναι, φιλότητι <b>good luck be</b> on our union,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11.248; εὐχωλῇς χαίρετε 13.358: χαῖρε ἀοιδῇ “Hymni Homerici” 9.7. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> <i>participle</i> χαίρων <b>glad, joyful,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.446, etc.; χαίροντα φίλην ἐς πατρίδ᾽ ἔπεμπον εἰς Ἰθάκην 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.461; χαίροντι φέρειν.. χαίρων 17.83 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; λυπούμενοι καὶ χαίροντες in sorrow and <b>in joy,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1356a16 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: also <i>perfect</i> <i>participle</i> κεχαρηκώς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.27, 42, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__IV.2</b></Level3> joined with another Verb, <b>safe and sound, with impunity,</b> χαίροντα ἀπαλλάσσειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 69, compare 9.106, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 24.153 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; more frequently with a <i>negative</i>, οὐ χαίρων <b>to one's cost,</b> οὐ χαίροντες γέλωτα ἐμὲ θήσεσθε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.29; οὔ τι χαίρων.. ἐρεῖς 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 363, compare “Ant.” 759, “Ph.” 1299, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 398, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 563, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 510d; οὐ γὰπ.. χαίρων τις.. τοὐμὸν ἀλγυνεῖ κέαρ 5th c.BC: Eupolis Comicus 90; οὔτε χαίροντες ἂν ἀπαλλάζαιτε 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 5.6.32; also οὔτι χαιρήσων γε σύ 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 186; compare above 11. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__IV.3</b></Level3> in the same sense as <i>imperative</i> (above [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 111), σὺ δέ μοι χαίρων ἀφίκοιο \">Refs</a>]<b>fare</b>-thee-<b>well,</b> and may'st thou arrive, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 15.128, compare 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 2.163 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; χαίροισ᾽ ἔρχεο go thy way <b>rejoicing,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica “Papyrus fragments” in E. Diehl, 23.7 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; ἀλλ᾽ ἑρπέτω χαίρουσα let her go <b>with a benison,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 819 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χαίρων ἴθι <b>fare</b>-thee-<b>well,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Alcestis” 813, “Ph.” 921; χαίρουσα.. στεῖχε [prev. author] “Hipp.” 1440. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__IV.4</b></Level3> τὸ χαῖρον τῆς ψυχῆς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.136c, 1089e. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__V</b></Level2> Astrology texts, of a planet, occupy the position appropriate to another of its own αἵρεσις, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-1st c.BC(?): Serapio Astrologus in “Catalogus Codicum Astrologorum” 8(4).230, 2nd c.AD: Ptolemaeus Mathematicus “Tetrabiblos” 51, 2nd c.AD: Vettius Valens Astrologus 63.6, 4th c.AD(?): Manetho Astrologus 2.348 \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]. (Cf. Sanskrit <i>háryati</i> 'take pleasure in', Umbr. <b>heriest</b> 'will wish', Latin <i>horior.</i>)","strongNumber":"G5463","accentedUnicode":"χαίρω","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G5479","matchingForm":"χαρά","stepTransliteration":"chara","gloss":"joy","_zh_tw_Gloss":"喜樂","_es_Gloss":"gozo","_zh_Gloss":"喜乐"},{"strongNumber":"G5485","matchingForm":"χάρις","stepTransliteration":"charis","gloss":"grace","_zh_tw_Gloss":"恩典","_es_Gloss":"gracia","_zh_Gloss":"恩典"}],"shortDef":"to rejoice","mediumDef":"<b>to rejoice, be glad, delighted; (as a greeting) Hail!, Greetings!; be joyful, be full of joy,</b> <ref='Mat.2.10; 5:12; 18:13'>Mt. 2:10; 5:12; 18:13</ref>; <ref='Mrk.14.11'>Mk. 14:11</ref>; <ref='Rom.12.12'>Rom. 12:12;</ref> <ref='2Co.2.3'>2Cor. 2:3;</ref> a term of salutation, <b>Hail!</b> <ref='Mat.26.49'>Mt. 26:49</ref>; <greek>λέγω χαιρειν</greek>, <b>to greet,</b> <ref='2Jn.10.11'>2Jn. 10:11;</ref> an epistolary forth, <b>Health!</b> <ref='Act.15.23'>Acts 15:23</ref>","stepGloss":"to rejoice","stepTransliteration":"chairō","count":74,"_es_Definition":"regocijarse, estar feliz, estar contento ; saludos, etc. (de salutaciones) ","_zh_tw_Definition":"1) 喜樂, 高興<br>2) 問候用語<br>  2a) 見面的口頭問候<br>  2b) 在信函開始附上的問候 #徒 15:23,23:26; 雅 1:1|","_zh_Definition":"1) 喜乐, 高兴<br>2) 问候用语<br>  2a) 见面的口头问候<br>  2b) 在信函开始附上的问候 #徒 15:23,23:26; 雅 1:1|","_step_Type":"verb","_vi_Definition":"vui mừng; vui vẻ; phấn khởi, hào hứng; vui thích, hài lòng; sự hoan hỉ, vui mừng","_zh_tw_Gloss":"歡喜","_es_Gloss":"regocijarse","_zh_Gloss":"欢喜"}]}